SIMPLE: slander
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slander
<hw>Slan"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>sclandere</ets>, OF. <ets>esclandre</ets>, <ets>esclandle</ets>,
<ets>escandre</ets>, F. <ets>esclandre</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>scandalum</ets>, Gr. <?/<?/<?/ a snare, stumbling block, offense,
scandal; probably originally, the spring of a trap, and akin to Skr.
<ets>skand</ets> to spring, leap. See <er>Scan</er>, and cf.
<er>Scandal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A false tale or report
maliciously uttered, tending to injure the reputation of another; the
malicious utterance of defamatory reports; the dissemination of
malicious tales or suggestions to the injury of another.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whether we speak evil of a man to his face or behind his back; the
former way, indeed, seems to be the most generous, but yet is a great
fault, and that which we call ⟦ldquo⟧reviling;⟦rdquo⟧ the latter is more
mean and base, and that which we properly call
⟦ldquo⟧<qex>slander</qex>⟦rdquo⟧, or ⟦ldquo⟧Backbiting.⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[We] make the careful magistrate⟦br⟧
The mark of <qex>slander</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1352 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Disgrace; reproach; dishonor; opprobrium.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou <qex>slander</qex> of thy mother's heavy womb.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Formerly, defamation generally,
whether oral or written; in modern usage, defamation by words spoken;
utterance of false, malicious, and defamatory words, tending to the
damage and derogation of another; calumny. See the Note under
<er>Defamation</er>.</def> <rj><au>Burril.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slander</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slander
<hw>Slan"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Slandered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Slandering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
defame; to injure by maliciously uttering a false report; to tarnish or
impair the reputation of by false tales maliciously told or propagated;
to calumniate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, do not <qex>slander</qex> him, for he is kind.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bring discredit or shame upon by one's
acts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tax not so bad a voice⟦br⟧
To <qex>slander</qex> music any more than once.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To asperse; defame; calumniate; vilify; malign;
belie; scandalize; reproach. See <er>Asperse</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slanderer</ent>⟦br⟧
